"smart_sources:000 Zettelkasten/The specificity of the L19 monoclonal antibody to tumour stroma in the central nervous system (CNS) and its proinflammatory characteristics position it as an exceptional candidate for immunotherapy..md": {"path":"000 Zettelkasten/The specificity of the L19 monoclonal antibody to tumour stroma in the central nervous system (CNS) and its proinflammatory characteristics position it as an exceptional candidate for immunotherapy..md","class_name":"SmartSource","history":[{"blocks":{"000 Zettelkasten/The specificity of the L19 monoclonal antibody to tumour stroma in the central nervous system (CNS) and its proinflammatory characteristics position it as an exceptional candidate for immunotherapy..md#":true,"000 Zettelkasten/The specificity of the L19 monoclonal antibody to tumour stroma in the central nervous system (CNS) and its proinflammatory characteristics position it as an exceptional candidate for immunotherapy..md#The remarkable specificity of the L19 monoclonal antibody to tumour stroma in the central nervous system (CNS) and its proinflammatory characteristics position it as an exceptional candidate for immunotherapy. L-19-based immunocytokines constructed by Weiss et al. (2020) demonstrate this antibody's ability to create a localised \"proinflammatory\" tumour environment. This is crucial for cancers such as glioblastoma that are considered to be an immunological desert. Previous literature also demonstrates how [[Enhancing the tumor microenvironment (TME) from an immunologically unresponsive state (\"cold\") to an inflammatory and activated state (\"hot\") can boost the effectiveness of immunotherapy interventions.]]{1}":true,"000 Zettelkasten/The specificity of the L19 monoclonal antibody to tumour stroma in the central nervous system (CNS) and its proinflammatory characteristics position it as an exceptional candidate for immunotherapy..md#References":true},"mtime":1709479648239,"size":902,"hash":"f2d8f1a728ee5edca2d1068805f0f