"smart_blocks:000 Zettelkasten/The specificity of the L19 monoclonal antibody to tumour stroma in the central nervous system (CNS) and its proinflammatory characteristics position it as an exceptional candidate for immunotherapy..md#": {"class_name":"SmartBlock","embeddings":{},"path":"000 Zettelkasten/The specificity of the L19 monoclonal antibody to tumour stroma in the central nervous system (CNS) and its proinflammatory characteristics position it as an exceptional candidate for immunotherapy..md#","heading":null,"length":64,"lines":[0,3],"key":"000 Zettelkasten/The specificity of the L19 monoclonal antibody to tumour stroma in the central nervous system (CNS) and its proinflammatory characteristics position it as an exceptional candidate for immunotherapy..md#"},
"smart_blocks:000 Zettelkasten/The specificity of the L19 monoclonal antibody to tumour stroma in the central nervous system (CNS) and its proinflammatory characteristics position it as an exceptional candidate for immunotherapy..md#The remarkable specificity of the L19 monoclonal antibody to tumour stroma in the central nervous system (CNS) and its proinflammatory characteristics position it as an exceptional candidate for immunotherapy. L-19-based immunocytokines constructed by Weiss et al. (2020) demonstrate this antibody's ability to create a localised \"proinflammatory\" tumour environment. This is crucial for cancers such as glioblastoma that are considered to be an immunological desert. Previous literature also demonstrates how [[Enhancing the tumor microenvironment (TME) from an immunologically unresponsive state (\"cold\") to an inflammatory and activated state (\"hot\") can boost the effectiveness of immunotherapy interventions.]]{1}": {"class_name":"SmartBlock","embeddings":{},"path":"000 Zettelkasten/The specificity of the L19 monoclonal antibody to tumour stroma in the central nervous system (CNS) and its proinflammatory characteristics position it as an exceptional candidate for immunotherapy..md#The remarkable specificity of the L19 monoclonal antibody to tumour stroma in the central nervous system (CNS) and its proinflammatory characteristics position it as an exceptional candidate for immunotherapy. L-19-based immunocytokines constructed by Weiss et al. (2020) demonstrate this antibody's ability to create a localised \"proinflammatory\" tumour environment. This is crucial for cancers such as glioblastoma that are considered to be an immunological desert. Previous literature also demonstrates how [[Enhancing the tumor microenvironment (TME) from an immunologically unresponsive state (\"cold\") to an inflammatory and activated state (\"hot\") can boost the effectiveness of immunotherapy interventions.]]{1}","heading":"The remarkable specificity of the L19 monoclonal antibody to tumour stroma in the central nervous system (CNS) and its proinflammatory characteristics position it as an exceptional candidate for immunotherapy. L-19-based immunocytokines constructed by Weiss et al. (2020) demonstrate this antibody's ability to create a localised \"proinflammatory\" tumour environment. This is crucial for cancers such as glioblastoma that are considered to be an immunological desert. Previous literature also demonstrates how [[Enhancing the tumor microenvironment (TME) from an immunologically unresponsive state (\"cold\") to an inflammatory and activated state (\"hot\") can boost the effectiveness of immunotherapy interventions.]]","length":15,"lines":[4,12],"key":"000 Zettelkasten/The specificity of the L19 monoclonal antibody to tumour stroma in the central nervous system (CNS) and its proinflammatory characteristics position it as an exceptional candidate for immunotherapy..md#The remarkable specificity of the L19 monoclonal antibody to tumour stroma in the central nervous system (CNS) and its proinflammatory characteristics position it as an exceptional candidate for immunotherapy. L-19-based immunocytokines constructed by Weiss et al. (2020) demonstrate this antibody's ability to create a localised \"proinflammatory\" tumour environment. This is crucial for cancers such as glioblastoma that are considered to be an immunological desert. Previous literature also demonstrates how [[Enhancing the tumor microenvironment (TME) from an immunologically unresponsive state (\"cold\") to an inflammatory and activated state (\"hot\") can boost the effectiveness of immunotherapy interventions.]]{1}"},
